    thinking: "**Defining App Specifications**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a solid grasp of the Gemini API\'s mechanics. My focus has shifted to pinpointing the essential features for crafting a refined, Android-like web application. The core requirement is clear: a user-friendly mobile app with an Android-centric design. I\'m prioritizing user experience and functionality.\n\n\n**Visualizing Login Flow**\n\nI\'m now diving deep into the onboarding process. Specifically, I am crafting the visual elements for the authentication screen. I envision a circular brand icon with a deep indigo background, paired with an open book material icon. The \"SoulJournal\" title will be displayed elegantly in EB Garamond. An animated tagline will cycle through key phrases. I also require a stylish image. Finally, I need a functional \"Sign in with Google\" button.\n\n\n**Refining Avatar Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating user profile data. I\'m prioritizing the user avatar, linking it to the Google profile image. I\'ve located the direct hotlink to the image, and confirming its use on the Today screen. I\'m updating the dashboard layout, which includes the rounded avatar with the journal title (\"Today\") in EB Garamond, and a settings cog. Plus, I need to incorporate the app version (\"SOULJOURNAL V1.0.4\") and a privacy disclaimer. I\'m focusing on design fidelity.\n\n\n**Designing Dashboard Display**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the dashboard\'s core element: the display of existing diary entries. I\'m visualizing them as pure white cards with refined typography, clearly showcasing the date, entry text, and mood tags. A key feature is the integration of a mock morning reflection text behind the card display, enhancing the visual depth of the layout. Also, I must ensure a dynamic grid of past entries or stats below the primary cards. The \"AI Summary\" floating action button is being prioritized.\n\n\n\n**Generating Dynamic Summaries**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the AI summary. This should dynamically leverage the Gemini API. My plan is to send active journal entries to an Express server for summary generation, utilizing `gemini-3.5-flash`. The prompt will incorporate user entries to generate real summaries with specific sections: Achievements, Actionable Vectors, and Emotional Tone. Also, I\'m integrating a footer with refined summary, copy, and share buttons. If no entries exist, the server will default to the mock reflection text. I\'ll need to configure full-stack capability! I\'ll build a server-side backend in `server.ts` to protect the API key.\n\n\n**Confirming Full-Stack Implementation**\n\nOkay, I\'ve reviewed the required scripts and build system updates to support full-stack functionality. The system instructions confirm how to handle `server.ts` and update `package.json`, which is a good reminder. I confirmed `tsx`, `esbuild`, and `express` are already in `package.json`, so I don\'t need to add new packages. This saves time, and simplifies the next steps. I am ready to implement the back-end.\n\n\n"
